In general, unaffiliated directors are similar to other new directors on most dimensions except that there is a noticeably smaller number who are female ($0.06$ versus $0.14$).
However, affiliated directors (i.e., employees or principals of members of the activist group) appear different: they are younger (51 years of age), rarely female ($0.01$).
While activist directors appear more likely to become members of the compensation committee in their first year of service ($0.32$ versus $0.27$ for directors not associated with activism campaigns), they are less frequently added to the audit committee ($0.26$), especially affiliated directors ($0.23$), than non-activism new directors ($0.35$).\footnote{SEC rules require a company to disclose whether it has at least one ``audit committee financial expert'' serving on its audit committee, and if so, the name of the expert and whether the expert is independent of management.
See \url{http://www.sec.gov/rules/final/33-8177.htm}.}

Panel B of Table \ref{tbl:dir_chars} presents data on the tenure of activist directors.
About $38\%$ of both affiliated and unaffiliated activist directors remain on their respective boards at the time of our data collection (September 2017).
Affiliated (unaffiliated) directors who have left their respective boards, did so after being on the board for 831 (812) days on average (i.e., they remained on the board for more than two years).
In many cases, their departure was associated with the company being acquired, going private, or going bankrupt.
Affiliated and unaffiliated activist directors who are still on their respective boards in December 31, 2017 have an average tenure of three or more years.
There is no apparent difference between affiliated and unaffiliated directors in these tenure statistics.

\subsection{Director elections: Voting outcomes}
In this section, we examine voting outcomes for activist directors.
Voting in director elections works as a way for the shareholders to communicate their satisfaction or dissatisfaction with performance.
We are interested in how the activist directors are considered differently by shareholders, looking at their voting outcomes following their appointment.
Table \ref{tbl:voting} provides results from OLS regressions where the dependent variable is \textit{Support}, the percentage of votes for the director based on data from ISS Voting Analytics.
Column 1 provides results from the voting outcomes in the year of activism while Columns 2 and 3 provide restuls from the voting outcomes in one year or two years following activism, respectively.
The results in Column 1 show that activist directors who are not directly affilaited with activists generally get higher support from the shareholders compared to the directors that are directly affiliated with activists.
The results might reflect that the shareholders have higher hopes for the activist directors who will bring out changes to the company in the beginning.
However, as we can see from Columns 2 and 3, this does not continue in the subsequent years.
First of all, activist directors get significantly higher level of support from shareholders in the year after activism event (0.8\% higher than other directors).
But the difference between the affiliated and unaffiliated directors is insignificant.
In two years after activism event, the difference goes away between activist directors and other directors.
The shareholder might treat activist directors the same as other directors as time passes and as they integrate with the company and other members of the board.

\subsection{Career outcomes} \label{sect:career}
In this section, we examine the career outcomes of activist directors following their appointment.
Table \ref{tbl:career} provides results from OLS regressions where the dependent variable is \textit{Departure(t,t+2)}, an indicator for the director leaving the board of the firm by year $t+2$ based on data from Eqular.
We separately examine affiliated and unaffiliated activist directors.
We find that it is the affiliated directors who gain other directorships in particular.
Holding other things constant, the affiliated directors gain 0.29 directorships in two years after their first appointment as can be found in Column (2).
The results are possibly driven by other activist campaigns run by the activist hedge fund they are affilaited with; as these activist hedge funds win other board seats in future campaigns, the affiliated directors who still work for the hedge fund would be more likely to have another board seat in those companies.

\section{Activist target selection} \label{sect:selection}
Prior research suggests that hedge fund activists typically target smaller firms, value-oriented firms (low market-to-book), and firms with sound operating cash flows but low sales growth, leverage and dividend payouts \citep*{Brav:2010gx}.
We extend this analysis to our sample and additionally examine whether the factors that are associated with activists seeking, or getting, board representation differ from those associated with activism in general.

%What type of firms do activists go after? When do activists demand board representation? When do they actually get a board seat? We next examine the likelihood of being targeted for activism as well as the likelihood of granting a board seat to activists.

We first examine the circumstances in which firms find themselves as the targets of activists.
Panel A of Table \ref{tbl:selection} reports the results of logistic regressions where the dependent variables are indicators for activism and the sample is the universe of firm-years meeting our sample requirements for the years 2004 to 2016.

The first column looks at the probability of being targeted for any kind of activism event, the second column examines the determinants of an activist making demands for board representation, and the third column examines the determinants of an activist getting representation on a firm's board.\footnote{Note that, in contrast to our other analyses, for the purpose of this table, our activism indicators are \emph{not} mutually exclusive.
That is, \textit{Activism} includes cases in any of the categories \textit{Non-board activism}, \textit{Board demand}, and \textit{Activist director}, while
\textit{Board demand} includes cases of \textit{Activist director} as well as cases where the board demands are not successful}
Consistent with prior research \citep{Brav:2008eu}, we find that size-adjusted return is negatively associated with being targeted by activists, consistent with activists targeting poorly performing firms.
Also, consistent with prior research, we find that smaller companies are more likely to be targeted.
We also find that activists are more likely to target firms with more directors, consistent with the number of directors being a proxy for poor governance and activists targeting firms with worse governance \citep{Yermack:1996wv}.
However, the significantly positive coefficient on \textit{Outside percent} is difficult to explain in the same way, as this measure is suggested by some to be a proxy for \emph{good} governance \citep{Bhagat:2008jc}.
We also see evidence that activists are more likely to target firms with greater portion of their shares held by institutional investors, consistent with these investors being more open to supporting activists.

In Panel B of Table \ref{tbl:selection}, we focus on activism events in examining two questions.
First, given that a firm has been targeted by activists, what are the factors that are associated with the activist demanding board seats?
Second, given that an activist has demanded board seats, what factors are associated with the activist's demands being met?
% Third, give that an activist has won board seats, what factors are associated with the activists themselves getting on the board?
We find evidence that conditional on selecting a firm as a target, an activist is more likely to demand board representation when the firm is smaller, when the firm performs worse and when leverage is lower.
In the second column, we see that performance and leverage are still negatively associated with getting a board seat conditional on asking for one.
Again activists are more likely to demand board representation at firms with more directors, consistent with activists being more inclined to seek board representation when targeting firms with worse governance \citep{Yermack:1996wv}.
We also see evidence that activists are more likely to get board representation when targeting firms with greater portion of their shares held by institutional investors, consistent with these investors being more open to supporting activist candidates.
In the last column, we additionally see that performance and payout are the most significant factors associated with having an activist director who is directly affiliated with the activist hedge fund.
We later examine specifically whether the market returns and payout improve when affiliated directors get on the board.
